{"key":"post-9499025","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9499025</id>\n<content>Is the bottom separating?&amp;nbsp; If so, it's probably from clogged filters, which cause the PC pressure to return to zero before the jars pressure does.&amp;nbsp; If jars have internal pressure, they'll break, usually by the bottom part separating.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A fix is to turn the burner the pressure cooker is on to 'low' for ten minutes or so before going to 'off'.&amp;nbsp; This will slow down the return to zero psi.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Some of my jars are over 20 years old.&amp;nbsp; I break more when canning fruits than pc'ing grains due to the fruits holding more mass and thus holding pressure if I accidentally put the rings on too tight.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9499031</next>\n<prev>9498974</prev>\n<first>9498974</first>\n<last>9504058</last>\n<when>1230347179</when>\n<utime>12/27/08 05:06 AM</utime>\n</post>"}